          <!-- PART 2: HOW TO TAKE THE ADVANCE -->
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Part 2 &#8212; How to Actually Pull a Cash Advance (All 4 Methods)</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">&#127998; Method 1 &#8212; ATM Withdrawal</strong><br>
              You need a 4-digit PIN. If you don't have one, call the number on the back of your card and ask them to mail you a cash advance PIN &#8212; it arrives in 7&#8211;10 business days. Do not try to set it over the phone; most issuers mail it for security.<br><br>
              At the ATM: insert card &#8594; select "Credit" or "Advance" (not "Debit") &#8594; enter PIN &#8594; enter amount. Most ATMs have a $500&#8211;$1,000 daily limit. There will be an ATM surcharge on top of your card's cash advance fee. Best for small, urgent amounts. Not ideal for stacking.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">&#127981; Method 2 &#8212; Bank Teller (Best for Large Amounts)</strong><br>
              Walk into any bank that is a Visa or Mastercard member &#8212; you do NOT need to be a customer of that bank. Bring your credit card and a government-issued photo ID.<br><br>
              Tell the teller: <em>"I'd like to do a cash advance on this Visa/Mastercard."</em> They will swipe or insert your card, you enter your PIN (or sign if no PIN required), and they hand you cash. There is no ATM daily limit &#8212; you can pull your full cash advance limit in a single teller visit: $5,000, $10,000, $20,000+. The only fees are your card's standard cash advance fee. Visa and Mastercard network rules require member banks to honor this transaction regardless of whether you bank there.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:#fbbf24">Pro tip:</strong> Go to a large bank branch (Chase, Wells Fargo, BofA) rather than a credit union. Large branch tellers handle this regularly without issue. Smaller branches may not have enough cash on hand for large advances &#8212; call ahead for amounts over $5,000.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">&#128203; Method 3 &#8212; Convenience Checks</strong><br>
              Your issuer mails physical checks drawn against your credit line. You write one to yourself and deposit it at your bank. Full step-by-step guide in the section directly below.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">&#128421;&#65039; Method 4 &#8212; Digital ACH / Direct Deposit (Cleanest Method)</strong><br>
              Some issuers let you push money from your credit line directly to your bank account via ACH &#8212; no ATM, no check, no physical interaction.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Citi Flex Cash:</strong> citicards.com &#8594; Account Management &#8594; Citi Flex Cash. Enter amount and bank routing/account number. Fixed rate (9.99&#8211;15.99%). Funds arrive in 1&#8211;2 business days.<br>
