          <!-- PART 3: STACKING -->
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Part 3 &#8212; How to Stack Cash Advances Across Multiple Cards</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              Stacking means pulling from multiple cards within a 24&#8211;48 hour window to build a large capital position. Issuers do not see each other's activity in real time &#8212; only on the next credit bureau update cycle (typically 30&#8211;45 days). This is a legal strategy and widely used. What matters is whether you have a clear repayment plan before you execute.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 1 &#8212; Know each card's available cash advance limit.</strong><br>
              Log into each card account or call the issuer. Your cash advance sub-limit is typically 20&#8211;30% of your credit limit. Write them all down:<br>
              Example: Citi $20K limit = $6,000 CA limit | Chase $15K limit = $3,000 CA limit | Capital One $12K limit = $3,600 CA limit | Discover $8K limit = $2,400 CA limit | BofA $10K limit = $3,000 CA limit<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.7)">Total available cash: $18,000</strong><br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 2 &#8212; Execute all pulls within 24&#8211;48 hours.</strong><br>
              Card issuers send bureau updates on their own schedule (not real time). A new cash advance on Card A will NOT appear on Card B's next credit pull for 30&#8211;45 days. Pull from all cards within the same 24&#8211;48 hour window to ensure no single issuer sees the others.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 3 &#8212; Use bank tellers for all large pulls.</strong><br>
              ATM daily limits ($500&#8211;$1,000) will slow you down significantly. Bank tellers have no daily cap on cash advance amounts. Visit different bank branches for each card &#8212; go to Wells Fargo for Card A, Chase for Card B, BofA for Card C. Any Visa/Mastercard member bank must process it.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 4 &#8212; Mix digital and physical methods.</strong><br>
              Use Citi Flex Cash and My Chase Loan digitally (same day). Pull Capital One and Discover at tellers the next morning. Use convenience checks from BofA the day after. This spreads timing naturally and avoids triggering fraud alerts from any single bank.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:#fbbf24">Real $25,000 Stack Example:</strong><br>
              Day 1 AM: Citi Flex Cash &#8212; $6,000 at 9.99% fixed &#8594; ACH to bank<br>
              Day 1 AM: My Chase Loan &#8212; $3,000 at 13.99% fixed &#8594; ACH to bank<br>
              Day 1 PM: Capital One teller advance &#8212; $3,600 @ 29.99% APR + 3% fee ($108)<br>
              Day 2 AM: Discover teller advance &#8212; $2,400 @ 24.99% APR + 5% fee ($120)<br>
              Day 2 PM: BofA promo convenience check &#8212; $8,000 @ 0% for 15 mo + 3% fee ($240)<br>
              Day 2 PM: BofA personal account deposit received<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Total cash: $23,000 &#8226; Total fees: ~$468 &#8226; Weighted average cost if held 30 days: ~$650 total &#8226; Net cost of $23K for 30 days = ~$1,118</strong><br><br>
              <strong style="color:#34d399">If you use the $23K for a business deal, short-term investment, or bridge gap with a clear 30-day exit &#8212; the cost is rational. If you're stacking to cover lifestyle expenses, this is a debt spiral.</strong><br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 5 &#8212; Repay highest-APR balances first.</strong><br>
              Cash advance interest starts day one. Rank your stack by APR descending and attack the most expensive balance first. Put Capital One (29.99%) and Discover (24.99%) at the top of the payoff order. Pay off the digital loans (Flex Cash, My Chase Loan) last since their fixed rates are lower and they have structured installments.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- PART 4: TRUE COST -->
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Part 4 &#8212; True Cost Formula Before You Pull Anything</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              Always calculate your all-in cost before touching any cash advance:<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Formula:</strong> (Amount &#215; Fee%) + (Amount &#215; APR% &#247; 365 &#215; Days Held) = Total Cost<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Example A &#8212; $5,000 pulled, repaid in 30 days, 3% fee, 25.99% APR:</strong><br>
              Fee: $150 &#8226; Interest: $5,000 &#215; 0.2599 &#247; 365 &#215; 30 = $107 &#8226; <strong style="color:#fbbf24">Total: $257</strong><br><br>

