          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">What Is a Convenience Check and How Does It Work?</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              A convenience check is a physical paper check your credit card issuer prints and mails to you. It looks exactly like a personal check &#8212; routing number, account number, issuer name &#8212; but instead of drawing from a bank account, it draws from your credit card's available credit line.<br><br>
              When you write one and deposit it, the amount is charged to your credit card exactly like a purchase or cash advance &#8212; <em>except</em> the issuer may have applied a special promotional APR to it. This is the critical point that separates a convenience check from a regular cash advance:<br><br>
              <strong style="color:#34d399">Regular cash advance:</strong> 3&#8211;5% upfront fee + 24&#8211;29.99% APR starting immediately, no grace period.<br>
              <strong style="color:#34d399">Promotional convenience check:</strong> 3&#8211;5% one-time fee + 0% APR for 12&#8211;21 months (sometimes 0% fee too). You borrow from your credit line and pay it back with zero interest during the promo window.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:#f87171">&#9888;&#65039; CRITICAL WARNING:</strong> Not every convenience check is a promo check. Some issuers mail standard cash advance checks that carry full APR. <strong>Before you write a single check, call the issuer and confirm the exact rate that will apply.</strong> The check itself may not tell you clearly. Call, get a verbal confirmation, write down: agent name, date, the APR, the fee, and the promo expiration date.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Where the Check Comes From and Where It Goes</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Source:</strong> Your credit card issuer (Citi, Chase, BofA, Discover, etc.) prints and mails these to cardholders they consider eligible &#8212; typically those with 6+ months of good standing and low utilization.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">What it looks like:</strong> A standard check with your name pre-printed, the issuer's bank routing number, and a unique account number tied to your credit card. It comes in a standard envelope &#8212; often labeled as a "special offer" which many people throw away. Never throw away mail from your card issuers unopened.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Where the money goes:</strong> You make it payable to yourself. You deposit it at your personal bank checking account &#8212; just like a regular check. The credit card company releases the funds to your bank, and the amount is charged to your credit card under the stated APR (promo 0% or standard cash advance rate).<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">When does your bank receive the money?</strong> Typically 1&#8211;3 business days. Some banks hold convenience checks for up to 5 days on first deposit. If you need it faster, take it to a teller rather than using mobile deposit &#8212; tellers can often override holds.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Step-by-Step: How to Use a Convenience Check</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Step 1 &#8212; Get the checks.</strong><br>
              Most issuers mail these to accounts in good standing. If you haven't received them, call and specifically ask:<br>
              <em>"I'd like to know if there are any promotional convenience checks or cash access offers available on my account right now."</em><br>
              Citi: 1-800-950-5114 &bull; Chase: 1-800-432-3117 &bull; BofA: 1-800-732-9194 &bull; Discover: 1-800-347-2683 &bull; Capital One: 1-800-227-4825<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Step 2 &#8212; Verify the terms BEFORE writing anything.</strong><br>
              Call the number printed on the check or on the back of your card. Ask:<br>
              (a) Is this check covered by a 0% promotional APR or the standard cash advance rate?<br>
              (b) What is the exact APR and the fee percentage?<br>
              (c) What is the exact promo expiration date?<br>
              (d) Is there a minimum amount I need to write the check for?<br>
              (e) How does payment allocation work &#8212; will my minimum payments go to this balance or to other balances first?<br>
              Write every answer down with the date and agent's name.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Step 3 &#8212; Fill it out correctly.</strong><br>
              &#8226; "Pay to the Order of" &#8212; Write your full legal name (exactly as it appears on your bank account).<br>
              &#8226; Amount &#8212; Write the dollar amount in numbers AND in words. Do not exceed your available credit or the check will bounce, causing fees on both ends.<br>
              &#8226; Date &#8212; Current date.<br>
              &#8226; Memo line &#8212; Write "Personal Transfer" or leave blank.<br>
              &#8226; Sign on the signature line.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Step 4 &#8212; Deposit at your bank.</strong><br>
              Try mobile deposit first (faster, convenient). If your bank rejects it on mobile (some banks flag convenience checks), go to a teller. Inform the teller it is a convenience check from a credit card issuer. Bring your ID. Ask the teller about the hold policy &#8212; if they say 5 days, ask if they can expedite with verified funds. Funds typically arrive in 1&#8211;3 business days for teller deposits.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Step 5 &#8212; Verify on your card statement within 48 hours.</strong><br>
              Log into your card account and confirm the transaction posted under the promotional APR &#8212; not as a standard cash advance. If the rate looks wrong, call the issuer immediately while you still have leverage to dispute the classification. If you wait, it becomes much harder to correct.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Which Cards Send 0% Convenience Checks Most Frequently</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Citi &#8212; #1 Issuer for This Strategy</strong><br>
              Citi sends 0% promotional check offers to established cardholders more consistently than any other major issuer. Typical terms: 0% for 12&#8211;21 months with a 3&#8211;5% fee (sometimes 0% fee promotions appear). In addition to physical checks, Citi offers <em>Citi Flex Cash</em> digitally &#8212; the same concept without paper. Log in &#8594; Account Management &#8594; Citi Flex Cash. Enter amount + your bank's routing/account number. Fixed APR (9.99&#8211;15.99%), no cash advance coding, funds in 1&#8211;2 days.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Bank of America &#8212; Consistent 0% Balance Transfer and Check Offers</strong><br>
              BofA sends combined balance transfer and convenience check promotions to established accounts. Typical: 0% for 12&#8211;15 months + 3% fee. Call 1-800-732-9194 and ask: <em>"Are there any current promotional check offers or balance transfer offers on my account?"</em> They can tell you over the phone without mailing anything.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Chase &#8212; My Chase Loan (Digital First)</strong><br>
              Chase rarely sends paper checks anymore but has <em>My Chase Loan</em> &#8212; a digital product that functions identically to a convenience check. Log into chase.com &#8594; Account Details &#8594; My Chase Loan. Select an amount, link your bank, funds are deposited at a fixed installment rate (typically 12&#8211;18%) with no cash advance fee and no cash advance APR. Clean, fast, and posts to your credit card as a structured loan.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Discover &#8212; Periodic Promo Check Mailings</strong><br>
              Discover sends promotional check offers to eligible accounts. Also offers phone-initiated direct deposits from your credit line under available promos. Call 1-800-347-2683. Ask specifically about "direct deposit promotions" rather than just "convenience checks" as they may frame it differently.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">US Bank &#8212; ExtendPay and Promo Mailings</strong><br>
              US Bank has <em>ExtendPay</em> (a plan-style feature) and sends promo check offers to established accounts. Log into usbank.com and check Account Services for ExtendPay options.<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Capital One &#8212; Less Frequent, Higher Rates</strong><br>
              Capital One occasionally sends convenience checks but the rates are typically at standard cash advance APR (26.99&#8211;29.99%). Always verify before using a Capital One check. Their Flex Loan product (when available) is a better option.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Stacking Convenience Checks &#8212; Multiple Cards, One Large Pool</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              If 3&#8211;4 cards are offering promotional checks simultaneously, stack them into a single capital pool. Space the deposits 2&#8211;3 days apart to avoid triggering bank fraud alerts (multiple large checks deposited in 24 hours can flag your account).<br><br>

              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Example stack with 4 cards:</strong><br>
              Day 1: Citi Flex Cash &#8212; $15,000 at 9.99% fixed &#8594; ACH deposit<br>
              Day 2: BofA 0% promo check &#8212; $10,000 at 0% for 15 months + $300 fee &#8594; teller deposit<br>
              Day 3: Discover 0% promo check &#8212; $6,000 at 0% for 12 months &#8594; mobile deposit<br>
              Day 4: My Chase Loan &#8212; $8,000 at 13.99% fixed &#8594; ACH deposit<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.7)">Total: $39,000 &#8226; Total fees paid: ~$300 &#8226; Park in HYSA at current APY for 12 months &#8212; at 5% that&#39;s ~$1,950 earned, net ~$1,650 after fees. <em style="color:var(--muted)">Note: HYSA rates move with the Fed &#8212; confirm current rate before calculating.</em></strong><br><br>

              <strong style="color:#fbbf24">Tracking Sheet (Mandatory):</strong> Keep a spreadsheet with: Card name, Amount, APR, Promo expiration date, Monthly minimum payment, and Payoff target date. Set phone calendar alerts 45 days before every expiration date. One missed deadline means deferred interest kicks in retroactively on some cards &#8212; wiping out all gains.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Mistakes That Will Kill This Strategy</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              &#10060; <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Using a standard cash advance check instead of a promo check.</strong> Always call and verify the rate. Never assume a check that arrived in the mail is at 0%.<br><br>
              &#10060; <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Missing the promo expiration date.</strong> Deferred interest on some cards means you get charged the full APR on the original amount from day one if you don't pay in full before expiration. This can turn a $300 fee into a $3,000+ bill overnight.<br><br>
              &#10060; <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Making only minimum payments thinking that's enough.</strong> Some issuers apply payments to the lowest-APR balance last. Citi is known for this. If you have a regular purchase balance AND a promo balance on the same card, your minimum payment may go entirely to purchases while your promo balance sits and eventually expires. Always pay more than the minimum when carrying a promo balance.<br><br>
              &#10060; <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Writing the check to a third party you don't control.</strong> Write to yourself only. If a third party disputes the service or product, the chargeback process is complicated when the original transaction was a cash advance check.<br><br>
              &#10060; <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Spending the float instead of investing or deploying it.</strong> This strategy only generates value if the cash earns more than it costs (HYSA, business investment) or enables a return greater than the fee. Using it to cover living expenses is just borrowing at cost.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

