        <!-- PHASE 1 -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:14px;border-color:rgba(168,85,247,.25);background:rgba(168,85,247,.04)">
          <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="width:36px;height:36px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(168,85,247,.2);border:2px solid rgba(168,85,247,.4);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:15px;color:#c084fc;flex-shrink:0">1</div>
            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#c084fc">Phase 1 — Audit Your Reports (Week 1)</div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--muted)">You cannot fix what you cannot see</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#c084fc">Pull All 3 Bureau Reports — Free</div>
            <div class="res-body">Go to annualcreditreport.com (the only federally mandated free source). Pull Experian, Equifax, and TransUnion simultaneously. You are entitled to free weekly reports under the 2020 amendment. Download all three as PDFs and save them. Do NOT use Credit Karma or Credit Sesame for disputes — they show Vantage scores, not FICO, and their dispute tools are limited.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#c084fc">What to Look For — Full Audit Checklist</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              Go line by line through each report. Flag anything that is:<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Not yours</strong> — accounts you never opened (possible fraud or mixed file)<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Wrong balance</strong> — any account showing a higher balance than your actual balance<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Wrong status</strong> — paid account still showing as open or delinquent<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Duplicate entries</strong> — same debt listed twice (once by original creditor, once by collector)<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Outdated items</strong> — negative items older than 7 years (10 for bankruptcy)<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Wrong date</strong> — date of first delinquency is incorrect (affects when item ages off)<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Wrong personal info</strong> — wrong address, misspelled name, wrong employer<br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">&#10003; Unauthorized inquiries</strong> — hard pulls you didn't authorize
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#c084fc">Score All 3 Reports</div>
            <div class="res-body">Once you've audited, rate each negative item on two dimensions: (1) How inaccurate or unverifiable is it? (High = dispute first.) (2) How much is it hurting your score? Collections and charge-offs within the last 2 years hurt the most. Late payments on accounts with high limits hurt most. Inquiries matter least. Create a priority list — most impactful and most disputable items go first.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PHASE 2 -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:14px;border-color:rgba(96,165,250,.25);background:rgba(96,165,250,.04)">
          <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="width:36px;height:36px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(96,165,250,.2);border:2px solid rgba(96,165,250,.4);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:15px;color:#60a5fa;flex-shrink:0">2</div>
            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#60a5fa">Phase 2 — Dispute Collections First (Weeks 2–3)</div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--muted)">Collections are the most removable — start here</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Step 1 — Send FDCPA §809 Debt Validation Letters</div>
            <div class="res-body">For EVERY collection account, send a debt validation letter to the collection agency (not the bureau) via USPS Certified Mail with Return Receipt. Under FDCPA §809(b), the collector must cease all collection activity — including credit bureau reporting — until they validate the debt. Send all at once. Mail from the post office and keep every receipt. Many collectors will simply delete rather than validate, especially on older debts.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">What a Valid Validation Must Include</div>
            <div class="res-body">If they respond, check the validation against these requirements: (1) The name and address of the original creditor. (2) The amount of the debt and a complete breakdown. (3) A copy of the original signed agreement (if you request it). (4) Proof they are licensed to collect in your state. If ANY of these are missing or incorrect, send a follow-up rejection letter and dispute the account with all 3 bureaus citing failure to properly validate.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Step 2 — Dispute Simultaneously with All 3 Bureaus</div>
            <div class="res-body">While the collector processes your validation request, send FCRA §611 dispute letters to Experian, Equifax, and TransUnion. Dispute each collection account with specific grounds: "This account cannot be verified. The collector has failed to provide adequate debt validation. I dispute the accuracy of this entry and request immediate investigation and deletion per FCRA §611." Send via Certified Mail. Bureaus have 30 days to investigate — if they cannot verify, they must delete.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Statute of Limitations — Know This Before Paying Anything</div>
            <div class="res-body">Every state has a statute of limitations (SOL) on debt — typically 3–6 years from the date of first delinquency. After the SOL expires, collectors cannot sue you. Making ANY payment — even $1 — can reset the SOL clock in many states. Check your state's SOL at nolo.com before sending a single dollar. If a debt is past the SOL, your response should be a cease and desist letter — not a payment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PHASE 3 -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:14px;border-color:rgba(52,211,153,.25);background:rgba(52,211,153,.04)">
          <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="width:36px;height:36px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(52,211,153,.2);border:2px solid rgba(52,211,153,.4);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:15px;color:#34d399;flex-shrink:0">3</div>
            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#34d399">Phase 3 — Dispute All Inaccuracies (Weeks 3–5)</div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--muted)">Tackle late payments, charge-offs, and errors across all bureaus</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">Late Payments — 3 Angles of Attack</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Angle 1 — Dispute inaccurate dates.</strong> If the late payment date reported is wrong by even one day, dispute it as factually inaccurate. Bureaus often cannot verify exact dates and will delete.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Angle 2 — Goodwill letter to original creditor.</strong> Write directly to the original creditor's customer relations department. Acknowledge the late, explain the hardship (job loss, medical, etc.), show your current perfect payment history, and request removal as a one-time goodwill gesture. Success rate: 30–40% for isolated lates on otherwise clean accounts.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">Angle 3 — Dispute with the bureau.</strong> Dispute the late payment directly with each bureau, citing any inaccuracy in the date, amount, or account status. Even if the late was real, bureaus sometimes fail to verify the exact details and must delete.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">Charge-Offs — How to Handle Them</div>
            <div class="res-body">A charge-off is when a creditor writes off your debt as a loss after 180 days of non-payment. It stays on your report for 7 years from the original delinquency date. Dispute the balance first — charge-offs often show inflated balances that are inaccurate. If the account has been sold to a collector, both the original creditor AND the collector may be reporting it — dispute the duplicate. If the charge-off is accurate, negotiate pay-for-delete with the original creditor or the collector who now owns it.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">Hard Inquiries — Fast and Easy Wins</div>
            <div class="res-body">You can dispute any inquiry you didn't authorize. Under FCRA §604, creditors can only pull your credit for "permissible purposes." Go through every inquiry and mark any you don't recognize or didn't authorize. Dispute with the bureau: "I did not authorize this inquiry and request its immediate removal under FCRA §604." Bureaus frequently delete inquiries on dispute — they're rarely worth fighting over, but each removal is a small score boost.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PHASE 4 -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:14px;border-color:rgba(251,191,36,.25);background:rgba(251,191,36,.04)">
          <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="width:36px;height:36px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(251,191,36,.2);border:2px solid rgba(251,191,36,.4);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:15px;color:#fbbf24;flex-shrink:0">4</div>
            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#fbbf24">Phase 4 — Build Positive History (Months 2–3)</div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--muted)">Removal alone is not enough — you must build</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#fbbf24">Secured Card Strategy</div>
            <div class="res-body">Open a secured card (Discover it Secured, Capital One Secured, or Chime Credit Builder). Use it for one small recurring charge — Netflix, gas, phone bill. Set autopay for the full balance each month. Never carry a balance. After 6–12 months of perfect payment history, most secured cards graduate to unsecured and your deposit is returned. This single action adds 40–80 points for thin-file applicants.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#fbbf24">Credit Builder Loan</div>
            <div class="res-body">A credit builder loan (Self, Credit Strong, or a local credit union) works in reverse — you make payments that are saved in a locked account, and the lender reports them as on-time installment payments. You get the money at the end. The purpose is the payment history, not the cash. Having both a revolving account (credit card) and an installment account (credit builder loan) reporting simultaneously maximizes your score mix factor.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#fbbf24">Authorized User Tradeline</div>
            <div class="res-body">Ask a family member or trusted friend with excellent credit to add you as an authorized user on their oldest, highest-limit card with a perfect payment history. You don't need to actually use or even receive the physical card. That account's full history — age, limit, and payment record — appears on your report within 30–45 days. This is completely legal and one of the fastest score boosts available. A single good tradeline can add 30–80 points within 45 days.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#fbbf24">Utilization Optimization — The Fastest Win</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              Credit utilization is 30% of your FICO score. The scoring formula is simple: keep all revolving balances below 10% of total credit limits for maximum points. Tactics:<br><br>
              &#10003; Pay balances BEFORE the statement closing date (not the due date)<br>
              &#10003; Request credit limit increases on all cards over 6 months old<br>
              &#10003; Spread balances across cards rather than maxing one out<br>
              &#10003; Never close old cards — it reduces available credit and hurts score<br>
              &#10003; If you need fast improvement, pay down to $0 on all cards before an important application
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PHASE 5 — ESCALATION -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:14px;border-color:rgba(239,68,68,.25);background:rgba(239,68,68,.04)">
          <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="width:36px;height:36px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(239,68,68,.2);border:2px solid rgba(239,68,68,.4);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:15px;color:#f87171;flex-shrink:0">5</div>
            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#f87171">Phase 5 — Escalation Tactics (Months 3+)</div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--muted)">When standard disputes fail, these moves apply pressure</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">CFPB Complaint — The Real Nuclear Option</div>
            <div class="res-body">File a complaint at consumerfinance.gov/complaint against any bureau that failed to properly investigate. Select "Credit reporting" then "Incorrect information on my report." Describe exactly what you disputed, when, and how they responded. The bureau must respond within 15 days. This escalates beyond the standard disputes team to a dedicated regulatory response team. CFPB complaints produce deletions at rates far higher than repeat disputes alone.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Method of Verification — Force Their Hand</div>
            <div class="res-body">After a bureau says an item is "verified," send a Method of Verification letter demanding they disclose: (1) The name, address, and phone number of the entity that verified the item. (2) The specific procedure used to verify. (3) All documents reviewed. Under FCRA §611(a)(7), they have 15 days to respond. Most bureaus conduct verification by sending an automated ACDV (Automated Consumer Dispute Verification) form to the creditor — they often can't provide actual documents. If they can't respond properly, the item must be deleted.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">State Attorney General Complaint</div>
            <div class="res-body">File with your state AG's consumer protection division simultaneously with a CFPB complaint. Most states have stronger consumer protection laws than federal FCRA. Dual regulatory pressure from both federal (CFPB) and state (AG) significantly increases bureau compliance. Find your state AG at naag.org. This costs nothing and takes 10 minutes.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">FCRA Lawsuit — The Last Resort That Works</div>
            <div class="res-body">If a bureau has verifiably violated FCRA — failed to investigate, continued reporting inaccurate information after dispute, or willfully ignored your rights — you have the right to sue under FCRA §616 and §617. Statutory damages: $100–$1,000 per violation, plus punitive damages and attorney fees. Many consumer protection attorneys handle these cases on contingency (no upfront cost). A certified letter from a consumer law attorney — before actual filing — produces immediate deletion in the vast majority of cases. Find a FCRA attorney at consumeradvocates.org or naca.net.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- LAWS REFERENCE -->
        <div class="card" style="border-color:rgba(96,165,250,.2)">
          <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:800;font-size:15px;color:#60a5fa;margin-bottom:12px">&#9878;&#65039; Key Laws Every DIY Repairer Must Know</div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">FCRA — Fair Credit Reporting Act</div>
            <div class="res-body"><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§609</strong> — Right to request copies of information in your file and documents used to verify it.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§611</strong> — Right to dispute inaccurate information. Bureau must investigate within 30 days and delete if unverifiable.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§611(a)(7)</strong> — Right to know the Method of Verification.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§623</strong> — Furnishers (creditors) must report accurate information. You can dispute directly with them.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§605</strong> — Limits on how long negative info can stay (7 years for most, 10 for bankruptcy).<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§604</strong> — Permissible purposes for pulling your credit.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§616-617</strong> — Your right to sue for willful or negligent noncompliance.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">FDCPA — Fair Debt Collection Practices Act</div>
            <div class="res-body"><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§807</strong> — Prohibits false representations in collecting a debt.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§809</strong> — Right to request debt validation within 30 days of first contact. Collector must cease activity until validated.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§805</strong> — Restricts when and how collectors can contact you. Send a cease and desist to stop all contact.<br><strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75)">§813</strong> — Right to sue for violations: up to $1,000 per violation plus damages and attorney fees.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Full Law Texts (Free)</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              FCRA full text: law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/15/1681<br>
              FDCPA full text: law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/15/1692<br>
              File CFPB complaint: consumerfinance.gov/complaint<br>
              Free annual reports: annualcreditreport.com<br>
              FTC Identity Theft: identitytheft.gov<br>
              Find FCRA attorney: naca.net or consumeradvocates.org
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
