          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Who Officially Qualifies</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              &#9989; Active duty, retired, or veteran members of the Army, Navy, Marine Corps, Air Force, Space Force, Coast Guard, or National Guard<br>
              &#9989; Department of Defense (DoD) civilian employees and contractors<br>
              &#9989; <strong style="color:#60a5fa">Immediate family members</strong> &#8212; spouses, children, parents, siblings, grandparents, and grandchildren of any qualifying member<br>
              &#9989; <strong style="color:#60a5fa">Household members</strong> of any existing Navy Federal member &#8212; anyone sharing the same address, regardless of relation<br><br>
              The household member path is the most overlooked. If anyone at your address is already a member, you qualify today.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">The Deceased Veteran Path &#8212; Even If They Passed Away</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              This is one of the most common real-world situations: you have a grandparent or parent who served, but they have since passed away. Navy Federal still honors family eligibility based on a deceased veteran&#39;s service. You do not need them to be alive to qualify.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">What to say when you call or apply online:</strong><br>
              <em style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.7)">&ldquo;My grandfather served in the [branch of service] and has since passed away. I&rsquo;d like to open a membership as an immediate family member based on his service.&rdquo;</em><br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">What they will ask:</strong><br>
              &#8226; The veteran&#39;s full legal name<br>
              &#8226; Branch of service (Army, Navy, Marines, Air Force, etc.)<br>
              &#8226; Approximate years served or service dates if known<br>
              &#8226; Your relationship (grandchild, child, etc.)<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">If you have no paperwork:</strong><br>
              Many families do not have the veteran&#39;s DD-214 or discharge papers, especially when the veteran passed long ago. Be straightforward about it:<br>
              <em style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.7)">&ldquo;My grandfather passed away when I was young and we no longer have his military records, but he served in the [branch]. Is there anything you can do to help verify or process my application?&rdquo;</em><br><br>
              Navy Federal has internal access to some DoD records and can sometimes verify service independently. They are known for working with families in exactly this situation. The representative will guide you through what they can look up on their end. If they need documentation, they will tell you specifically what to provide &#8212; not everything requires the DD-214.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Helpful documents if you have any:</strong><br>
              &#8226; DD-214 (discharge papers &#8212; your family may have this filed somewhere)<br>
              &#8226; Death certificate<br>
              &#8226; Your own birth certificate showing relationship (e.g., your parent is named, linking you to the veteran)<br>
              &#8226; Any military ID cards, service medals, or pension letters referencing the veteran
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">The Household Member Path &#8212; Easiest Route</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              If you know <em>anyone</em> who is already a Navy Federal member and you share a household address with them &#8212; a friend, roommate, significant other, family member &#8212; you qualify as a household member.<br><br>
              1. Confirm the existing member is willing to confirm the household connection<br>
              2. Apply at navyfederal.org &#8594; Membership &#8594; Apply Now<br>
              3. Select &ldquo;Household Member of a Navy Federal Member&rdquo;<br>
              4. Enter the existing member&#39;s name and membership number (they can provide this from their app or statement)<br>
              5. Provide your own ID and address<br><br>
              Your accounts are entirely separate. The existing member is not responsible for your account and does not co-sign anything. They simply confirm the shared household.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">How to Apply</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Online:</strong> navyfederal.org &#8594; &ldquo;Join Now&rdquo; &#8594; Select eligibility category &#8594; Enter your information<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">By phone (recommended for complex situations):</strong> <strong style="color:#60a5fa">1-888-842-6328</strong> &#8212; available 24/7. Calling is the best option when your path involves a deceased veteran or you&#39;re unsure which category applies. Representatives are knowledgeable and genuinely helpful.<br><br>
