            <div>
              <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:17px;color:#34d399">American Consumer Council (ACC)</div>
              <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);margin-top:2px">The backdoor into hundreds of credit unions &#8212; open to almost anyone</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:12px 16px;border-radius:10px;background:rgba(52,211,153,.08);border:1px solid rgba(52,211,153,.2);font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,.7);line-height:1.75;margin-bottom:14px">
            Most credit unions have strict membership requirements &#8212; you have to live in a certain area, work for a specific employer, or belong to a specific group. The American Consumer Council is a nonprofit organization that serves as a partner sponsor for hundreds of credit unions across the country. Joining the ACC makes you eligible for credit union membership even if you have no other qualifying connection. This is one of the most underused financial access strategies available.
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">What Is the American Consumer Council?</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              The American Consumer Council (americanconsumers.org) is a nonprofit consumer education and advocacy organization founded in 1987. Its primary financial benefit for members is this: the ACC has formal partnership agreements with a large network of credit unions that agree to accept ACC members as eligible to join &#8212; regardless of where they live, where they work, or who they know.<br><br>
              Joining the ACC is essentially paying a small fee to gain a qualifying &ldquo;association membership&rdquo; that unlocks credit union access. This is entirely legal &#8212; credit unions are permitted to define their fields of membership by group association, and the ACC is one such recognized group.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">How to Join the ACC &#8212; Step by Step</div>
            <div class="res-body">
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 1 &#8212; Go to americanconsumers.org</strong><br>
              Navigate to the membership section. Individual membership is typically $8 per year. Some credit unions will waive this fee or pay it on your behalf when you apply through their ACC partner link.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 2 &#8212; Select Individual Membership</strong><br>
              Fill in your name, address, and email. Pay the annual membership fee. You will receive a membership confirmation and number &#8212; this is your credential for applying to ACC-partner credit unions.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 3 &#8212; Use Your ACC Membership to Apply to a Credit Union</strong><br>
              When applying to an ACC-partner credit union, select &ldquo;Association Membership &#8212; American Consumer Council&rdquo; as your eligibility category. Enter your ACC membership number. Many credit unions accept this digitally with no additional verification needed.<br><br>
              <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">Step 4 &#8212; Open the savings account</strong><br>
              Most credit unions require a small initial deposit ($5&#8211;$25) into a share savings account to establish membership. Once that is done, you have full access to their cards, loans, and rates.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="res-card">
            <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">Which Credit Unions Accept ACC Members</div>
            <div class="res-body">
