    <!-- SOFT VS HARD EXPLAINED -->
    <div id="pull-tab-softhard" style="padding:24px 0">
      <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:12px;border-color:rgba(52,211,153,.25);background:rgba(52,211,153,.04)">
        <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#34d399;margin-bottom:12px">What Is a Soft Pull?</div>
        <div class="res-card" style="margin-bottom:8px">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">Soft Pull &#8212; No Credit Impact</div>
          <div class="res-body">A soft inquiry is a credit check that does NOT affect your FICO score and is NOT visible to other lenders. Soft pulls are used for: pre-qualification checks, background checks, account reviews by existing lenders, and personal credit monitoring. You can have 50 soft pulls in a year and your score will not move a single point.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="res-card">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#34d399">When to Use Pre-Qualification (Soft Pull) First</div>
          <div class="res-body">Always use the issuer&#39;s pre-qualification tool before submitting a formal application. Pre-qual is a soft pull &#8212; it shows likely approval odds without any score impact. Only proceed to the formal application (hard pull) if the pre-qual shows strong approval likelihood. This protects your client&#39;s score by only triggering hard pulls on applications with high odds of approval.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:12px;border-color:rgba(239,68,68,.25);background:rgba(239,68,68,.04)">
        <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#f87171;margin-bottom:12px">What Is a Hard Pull?</div>
        <div class="res-card" style="margin-bottom:8px">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Hard Pull &#8212; Impacts Score</div>
          <div class="res-body">A hard inquiry is triggered when you formally apply for credit. It appears on your credit report, is visible to other lenders, and typically drops your FICO score 2&#8211;8 points per inquiry. Hard pulls remain on your report for 2 years but only impact your score for 12 months. After 12 months the score impact disappears entirely, though the inquiry still shows on the report.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="res-card" style="margin-bottom:8px">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Rate Shopping Exception &#8212; FICO Groups Inquiries</div>
          <div class="res-body">For mortgages, auto loans, and personal loans &#8212; FICO groups all inquiries of the same type within a 14&#8211;45 day window and counts them as ONE inquiry. This does NOT apply to credit cards. You can apply to 5 personal loan lenders in one week and FICO counts it as a single hard pull. Credit cards each count separately &#8212; 5 card applications = 5 separate inquiries.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="res-card">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#f87171">Hard Pull Strategy for Card Stacking</div>
          <div class="res-body">
            When stacking credit cards:<br>
            &#8226; Apply Chase cards first (most sensitive to recent inquiries)<br>
            &#8226; Wait 7&#8211;10 days before Citi applications<br>
            &#8226; Wait another week before Wells Fargo<br>
            &#8226; Apply BofA, Discover, US Bank in month 2<br><br>
            Each application does trigger a hard pull but by spacing them, each issuer sees fewer inquiries at the moment of their pull. The total score impact for a 10-card stack is typically 30&#8211;60 points &#8212; which recovers fully within 12&#8211;18 months as the accounts age and payment history accumulates.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-color:rgba(96,165,250,.2)">
        <div style="font-family:'Cabinet Grotesk',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:16px;color:#60a5fa;margin-bottom:12px">Score Recovery After a Hard Pull Stack</div>
        <div class="res-card">
          <div class="res-title" style="color:#60a5fa">Timeline</div>
          <div class="res-body">
            <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Month 1&#8211;3:</strong> Score may dip 30&#8211;60 points from multiple hard inquiries. New accounts lower average age of credit.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Month 4&#8211;6:</strong> Score stabilizes as payment history builds. New available credit actually improves utilization ratio.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Month 7&#8211;12:</strong> Score typically recovers to original level or higher if utilization is kept low and all payments are on time.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.8)">Month 13+:</strong> Hard pull impact drops to zero. Accounts are now aging and contributing positively. Score often ends up 20&#8211;40 points higher than pre-stack if the accounts are well-managed.
          </div>
        </div>
